   I, Antcrusher, worked on converting soft_dri (as it was the only
file I had) into a new inheritable for generic drinks.  From what I
could tell, alco_dri.c ran instant healing and intoxication off one
variable.  Likewise, soft_dri.c ran instant healing and soaked off one
variable.  This object will do all three, and they are driven by
different variables so you can set each separately.  It can be used to
replace alco_dri and soft_dri.

   Note that the price for the alcoholic healing is less than the instant
healing by a factor of 3.  You get three points for every point of
alco_strength, but since it's on a time delay it seems fair.
   Thus, to figure your value for an item, it is still 4*x + (x^2)/10.  But
here, x is the AVERAGE of healing and alco_strength.  (Note that the
'standard' pub drinks are far overpriced.)

   Soft_strength doesn't really do much except keep you from
drinking more soft drinks too soon.  This value does not contribute to
healing at all.  The sum of the soft_strength and alco_strength should
equal the healing value (or more), in order to keep instant healing
from being too easily available.

   This object now inherits treasure.c, so all the functions from it
can be used as well, including treasure and material types.  It
automatically sets to container and drink when created, and type
drink is removed automatically when drunk.
 
   This object is a standard drink object and works
   like /obj/food.c or /obj/armour.c
 
   To use this you can do:
     inherit "obj/gene_dri";
   ......
   or,

   object oObj;
   oObj = clone_object("obj/gene_dri");
   oObj->set_name("tequila");
 
   These functions are defined in addition to those on treasure:

     set_soft_strength(int)     To set the soaking power of the item. If
          you don't wish the item to soak players just set this value to 0.
          This value has nothing to do with healing...it simply keeps
          players from drinking more soft drinks too soon.

     set_alco_strength(int)     To set the amount of intoxication.  The
          player will receive three (or whatever it is set to on your
          MUD) extra hit points for half this number of 'healing rounds',
          which I believe is every tenth heartbeat, usually.  If you
          don't want it to be intoxicating then (you could have used
          obj/soft_dri) set this to 0.  Does not check for negatives.

     set_healing(int)   To set the amount of instant healing.

     set_drinker_mess(string)   To set the message that is written
          to the player when he drinks the item.

     set_drinking_mess(string)  To set the message given to the
          surrounding players when this object is drunk.

     set_empty_container(string)        The container of the liquid inside.
          For example "bottle" or "jug".

This following is an example of a drink.  It's the way the
beer from the pub looks now.  A drink like this was not possible using
alco_dri, the pub drinks inherited a special file (because healing
and alco level were driven by different variables, and alco_dri
couldn't handle it).

#include <mudlib.h>
inherit DRINK;
 
void reset(int iArg) {
  ::reset(iArg);
  if (iArg) return;
 
  set_name("beer");
  set_alt_name("alcohol"); /* for use in pub */
  set_short("a bottle of beer");
  set_value(12);
  set_weight(1);
  set_drinker_mess("That feels good.\n");
  set_healing(0);
  set_alco_strength(2);
  set_soft_strength(0);
  set_empty_container("bottle");
}

